nd hugely consequential illustration. In a story spanning more than a century, from Victorian Britain to America in the Space Age, Gowan Dawson traces the interconnected histories of the two most important versions of the image: the frontispiece to Thomas Henry Huxley’s Evidence as to Man’s Place in Nature (1863) and “The Road to Homo Sapiens,” a fold-out illustration in the best-selling book Early Man (1965). Dawson explores how the recurring appearances of this image pointed to shifting scientific and public perspectives on human evolution, as well as indicated novel artistic approaches and advancements in technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBiological illustration. 0aEvolution (Biology) in art. 0aPaleontological illustration. 0aScientific illustration. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074979340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300277234?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300277234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300277234/original  a978-3-11-074979-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles